## Why it matters

Imagine a busy restaurant where every waiter keeps running to a single tiny kitchen door the moment an order arrives — when the door jams, every waiter queues up and the whole restaurant grinds to a halt. In distributed systems, a slow or failing service acts like that jammed door: retries, timeouts, and increased concurrency can cascade and bring down otherwise healthy services.

The **circuit breaker pattern** acts like an electrical breaker or the restaurant manager who stops sending new orders to the jammed kitchen and uses a fallback plan until the kitchen is healthy again. It prevents repeated attempts that will likely fail, protects capacity, and gives the failing dependency time to recover.

---

## High-level idea (Analogy)

- *Closed*: Normal flow — requests go through. The system tracks failure rate.
- *Open*: Too many failures — short-circuit new requests immediately and return a fallback or error.
- *Half-Open*: After a cooldown, allow a few test requests to probe whether the dependency recovered.

This is like a door that is kept closed when the kitchen is broken, then you let a few orders through to check if the kitchen is working again.

---

## How it works (flowchart)

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  Client[Client] --> CB{Circuit State}
  CB -->|Closed| Call[Call upstream service]
  CB -->|Open| Fallback[Return fallback / error fast]
  Call --> Upstream[Upstream service]
  Upstream -->|Success| CBSuccess[Record success]
  Upstream -->|Failure| CBFail[Record failure]
  CBFail -->|Threshold reached| Trip[Open circuit]
  CBSuccess -->|In half-open| Reset[Reset to Closed]
```

---

## Typical sequence (time series)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
  Client->>Circuit: Request
  Circuit->>Upstream: Forward (if Closed / Half-Open)
  Upstream-->>Circuit: Success / Failure
  alt Failure
    Circuit-->>Client: Fast error or fallback
  else Success
    Circuit-->>Client: Response
  end
```

---

## Before / After (quick comparison)

| Without Circuit Breaker | With Circuit Breaker |
|-------------------------|----------------------|
| Every failure causes retries and queueing -> downstream overload | Failing dependency is short-circuited; callers fail fast or use fallback |
| High latency spikes cascade across services | Isolated failures, predictable degradation |
| Hard to distinguish healthy vs overloaded states in logs | Circuit metrics give clear failure signals |

---

## When to use it

- Any service that depends on external or flaky dependencies (third-party APIs, databases under load, remote microservices).
- When you want graceful degradation (fallback responses, cached results) rather than total outage.
- When you need to protect your system’s capacity during partial failures.

Avoid using it for trivial calls where the overhead of state tracking outweighs benefit.

---

## Practical knobs and patterns

- **Failure criteria**: Use error rate (e.g., >50% failures over last N requests) and/or slow responses (latency exceeds threshold) to count as failures.
- **Sliding window vs rolling counters**: Sliding windows are more accurate; simple counters with reset are cheaper but noisier.
- **Minimum throughput**: Only trip after a minimum number of requests to avoid tripping on low traffic noise.
- **Open timeout**: How long to stay Open before trying again (cooldown).
- **Half-open probe**: Allow M test requests and decide: success -> close; failure -> re-open and extend timeout.
- **Fallback strategy**: Return cached data, stale-but-available result, a default response, or a descriptive error.

---

## Common pitfalls

- *Over-eager tripping*: Too low a threshold causes unnecessary opens during short blips. Use minimum request counts and smoothing.
- *Too long cooldown*: Keeps callers blocked for too long; choose exponential backoff or capped backoff.
- *Poor fallback*: Returning a useless fallback is worse than surfacing the failure; design meaningful fallbacks (cache, degraded experience).
- *Single shared circuit state in distributed systems*: If one instance trips and others don’t, you may get uneven behavior. Consider sharing metrics or using local circuits per process with consistent fallback behavior.
- *State explosion*: Tracking per upstream endpoint/method can create many circuits — group logically where appropriate.
- *Mixing retries incorrectly*: Retries plus circuit breakers must be coordinated. Use limited retries inside closed state; avoid retries during open state (they’re pointless).

---

## Example — Minimal JS circuit breaker (concept)

```javascript
// naive circuit breaker for demo
class CircuitBreaker {
  constructor(action, {failureThreshold = 5, successThreshold = 2, timeout = 10000} = {}) {
    this.action = action; // async function
    this.failureThreshold = failureThreshold;
    this.successThreshold = successThreshold;
    this.timeout = timeout;

    this.state = 'CLOSED';
    this.failures = 0;
    this.successes = 0;
    this.nextAttempt = 0;
  }

  async fire(...args) {
    if (this.state === 'OPEN') {
      if (Date.now() > this.nextAttempt) {
        this.state = 'HALF';
      } else {
        throw new Error('CircuitOpen');
      }
    }

    try {
      const res = await this.action(...args);
      this._onSuccess();
      return res;
    } catch (err) {
      this._onFailure();
      throw err;
    }
  }

  _onSuccess() {
    this.failures = 0;
    if (this.state === 'HALF') {
      this.successes += 1;
      if (this.successes >= this.successThreshold) {
        this._reset();
      }
    }
  }

  _onFailure() {
    this.failures += 1;
    if (this.failures >= this.failureThreshold) {
      this._trip();
    }
  }

  _trip() {
    this.state = 'OPEN';
    this.nextAttempt = Date.now() + this.timeout;
    this.successes = 0;
  }

  _reset() {
    this.state = 'CLOSED';
    this.failures = 0;
    this.successes = 0;
  }
}

// usage: wrap a fetch/HTTP call in the action
```

Note: real-world implementations are more robust (sliding windows, bulkhead integration, metrics, dynamic thresholds).

---

## Monitoring and observability

Track these metrics per circuit:
- state changes over time (Closed/Open/Half)
- failure rate and success rate
- number of requests short-circuited (fast-fails)
- latency percentiles for proxied calls

These make it clear whether the circuit is protecting the service or masking systemic problems.

---

## Quick checklist before shipping

- [ ] Define failure criteria (errors and latency thresholds)
- [ ] Set minimum request volume to avoid flapping
- [ ] Choose cooldown and half-open probe counts
- [ ] Implement meaningful fallbacks
- [ ] Emit metrics and alerts on state changes
- [ ] Test with chaos/traffic injection to validate behavior

---

## Closing thought

Circuit breakers don't make failures disappear — they turn unexpected, noisy failures into controlled, observable degradation. That control buys you time to heal dependencies, deliver graceful fallbacks, and protect your system's capacity.

